In this script we try and figure out how to use SARIMA and a GARCH model to fit the flu data. To read more about the data, see: https://predict.phiresearchlab.org/legacy/flu/targets.html and https://github.com/cdcepi/flu-tools-2015-16

To get the data see the data-pulling.R script in the code folder.

GARCH is often used on the difference of the log values (roughly the percent change). GARCH can be viewed sort of like an ARMA that accounts for non-constant variance. Thus, we will first try to fit an ARMA model for the difference of the logs, which is what GARCH is usually performed on.

dILI <- as.ts(diff(log(train_series$ILI)))

ILI_auto_arima <- auto.arima(dILI, stepwise = FALSE, approximation = FALSE, trace=FALSE)
arimaorder(ILI_auto_arima)
## [1] 1 0 1

What happens if we make the period 52 weeks:

That looks better on the p-values, but a bit funky in the first 52 standardized residuals.

Well use that first SARIMA to predict the test set (since we cant use the periodic component for GARCH anyways)

And we can calculate the mean absolute error of our predictions:

mean(abs(ILI_preds$residuals))
## [1] 0.06770364

Next we try to build a GARCH model using an ARMA(1,1) (similar to the one we got with auto.arima()). But we need to try a few GARCH(m,r) models

The GARCH package in R doesnt seem to allow you to make predictions with the same model for a new set of data. Instead, you need to re-fit the model after each step and predict the next one. This means that it has more information than the SARIMA one does for making predictions at each step, as the SARIMA is only fit to the training data.

whole_series <- bind_rows(train_series, test_series)
garch_preds <- c()
for(i in 0:(nrow(test_series)-2)){
    new_train <- whole_series[1:(nrow(train_series)+i),]
    new_dILI <- as.ts(diff(log(new_train$ILI)))
    new_fit <- garchFit(~arma(1,1)+garch(1,1), new_dILI, trace=F)
    garch_preds[i+1] <- predict(new_fit, n.ahead=1)$meanForecast
}

Unlike SARIMA, the GARCH model does not miss over the top, but rather by not going far enough in its predictions. The MAE is similar to that of the SARIMA model (but worse, despite having a data advantage):

mean(abs(testILI-garch_preds))
## [1] 0.07066403

Lastly, lets see what happens if we convert these values back to their original form and take the MAEs:

ILI_SARIMA <- exp(cumsum(c(log(train_series$ILI[nrow(train_series)]),ILI_preds$residuals))[-1])
mean(abs(ILI_SARIMA-test_series$ILI[-nrow(test_series)]))
## [1] 0.4116419
ILI_GARCH <- exp(cumsum(c(log(train_series$ILI[nrow(train_series)]),garch_preds))[-1])
mean(abs(ILI_GARCH-test_series$ILI[-nrow(test_series)]))
## [1] 0.5490981
ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x=1:208, y=test_series$ILI[-nrow(test_series)])) +
    geom_line(aes(x=1:208, y=ILI_SARIMA), color="red", linetype="dashed") +
    geom_line(aes(x=1:208, y=ILI_GARCH), color="blue", linetype="dotted")

After transformation, you can see that the GARCH method is really looking for reversion to the mean and not doing a good job at all of capturing the peaks or nadirs. Seems like the SARIMA model is better for use with this dataset.
